07752nam a22009375i 9781463241872DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020021673  a97814632418727 a10.31826/97814632418722doi  a(DE-B1597)563219  a(OCoLC)1157769098  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPJ7737 4aPJ7737b.E53 2020 7aLCO0030002bisacsh04a398.222300aEndless Inspiration :bOne Thousand and One Nights in Comparative Perspective /ced. by Orhan Elmaz. 1aPiscataway, NJ : bGorgias Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGorgias Handbooks00tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tSECTION 1: LITERATURE -- tShahrazad in Twentieth-Century Fiction: Approaches and Considerations -- t“We Are Not in Baghdad Anymore”: Textual Travels and Hausa Intertextual Adaptation of Selected Tales of One Thousand and One Nights in Northern Nigeria -- tEnchanted Storytelling: Muḥammad Khuḍayyir between Borges and Shahrazad -- tTwo Perspectives, One Shahrazad: Turkish Poetry and One Thousand and One Nights -- tSECTION 2. MANUSCRIPTS -- tSource of Inspiration, Matter of Translation, Joseph von Hammer and the 1001 Nights -- t‘Oh Leader of Women in the World, oh Shahrazad!’ The Ending of the One Thousand and One Nights in the Earliest Turkish Translation and its Relationship to the Arabic Versions -- tLearning Over-Nights: Calcutta One as an Adaptation for Learners of Arabic -- tSECTION 3. MIDDLE EASTERN NARRATIVE CULTURES -- tIn and Out of the Nights: The Thousand and One Nights as an Introduction to Middle Eastern Narrative Culture -- tFrom Shahriyār’s Palace to the Streets of Morocco: A Comparative Study of the Moroccan Oral Tale ‘Ḥātim and the Queen Cobra’ with the ‘Story of Ḥāsib Karīm al- Dīn and the Queen Cobra’ in the One Thousand and One Nights -- tSECTION 4. PERFORMING ARTS -- tThe Slippers That Keep Coming Back: Gender and Race in Two Swedish Theatre Adaptations, Abu Casem’s Slippers (1908) and The Weaver of Baghdad (1923) -- tMiguel Gomes’s Arabian Nights trilogy: representing the Portuguese crisis through the imaginary world of The Thousand and One Nights -- tRussian Orientalist Ballet and Non-Russian National Opera: From Diaghilev to Miroshnichenko0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat we know in European literature as One Thousand and One Nights was born as a transnational text 300 years ago. In the exact same manner, the ‘original’ tales of those early translations were born prior to the ninth century in Baghdad, by collecting and incorporating earlier tales from other cultures and literary traditions and elaborating them while appropriating them into the local culture at the same time. At times, these tales are transformations of other, earlier tales, and at times, they have striking parallels with other and later tales, which clearly demonstrates how entangled the literary world is in the past and in present times. This volume deals with One Thousand and One Nights in yet another and novel way, bringing old and new together by exploring parallels and possible origins of its tales, as well as the wealth of modern and contemporary material that it has originated and continues to inspire. The chapters included bridge any borders imposed by time and space as well as genre, and – most of all – language. They address the theory and practice of the adaptation and appropriation of One Thousand and One Nights into literature, arts, and media, while approaching a definition of our contemporary knowledge and understanding of the Nights. Thus, it underlines the dynamic nature and autonomous life that the tale collection acquired and contributes to analyzing its role in Middle Eastern narrative culture as well as its influence on world literature on one hand, and its colourful manifestations in the performing arts on the other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAncient, Classical & Medieval. 4aLiterary Collections. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aCaiani, Fabio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherkaoui, Driss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobham, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemirkol, Neslihan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElmaz, Orhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElmaz, Orhan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalpakli, Mehmet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeuwen, Richard van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarzolph, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelville, Firuza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRooke, Tetz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomann, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUba Adamu, Abdalla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVera, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWentker, Sibylle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Lite